### CSS Text Transform

**text-transform** controls the capitalization of text.

---

### Values

| Value | Effect | Example |
|-------|--------|---------|
| `none` | No change (default) | "Hello World" |
| `uppercase` | ALL CAPS | "HELLO WORLD" |
| `lowercase` | all lowercase | "hello world" |
| `capitalize` | First Letter Of Each Word | "Hello World" |
| `full-width` | Full-width characters | "Ｈｅｌｌｏ" |
| `full-size-kana` | Katakana conversion | |

---

### Uppercase

```css
h1 {
  text-transform: uppercase;
}
/* Input: "Welcome to our site" */
/* Output: "WELCOME TO OUR SITE" */
```

---

### Lowercase

```css
.email {
  text-transform: lowercase;
}
/* Input: "User@Example.COM" */
/* Output: "user@example.com" */
```

---

### Capitalize

```css
.title {
  text-transform: capitalize;
}
/* Input: "this is a title" */
/* Output: "This Is A Title" */
```

---

### Common Use Cases

```css
/* Force headings to uppercase */
h2 {
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 2px;
}

/* Normalize email inputs */
input[type="email"] {
  text-transform: lowercase;
}

/* Style navigation */
.nav a {
  text-transform: uppercase;
  font-size: 0.9rem;
  font-weight: 600;
}

/* Keep code lowercase */
code {
  text-transform: none;
}
```

---

### Important Notes

- `capitalize` capitalizes **every** word, even short words like "the" or "and"
- Text transform does **not** change the actual DOM content
- The original text remains in the source; only the display changes
- Screen readers read the original text, not the transformed version

> **Best Practice:** Use `text-transform` for presentational capitalization. Don't rely on it for data - the original value stays unchanged.
